lespauled: I think there is a concept of &quot;good enough&quot;, but right now a lot of organizations treat usability as something separate from the product and as extra features, then say they don&#039;t have time to make a perfect product and will make something good enough (meaning they will spend less time on usability). My perspective is that you need to start with the user and add features with the user in mind. By default you then make something that does what a user needs, the question is then how long you spend making it really smooth for them, how many additional features you, and whether there is anything on the outstanding bug list that prevents it from being &quot;good enough&quot; for the user to get their job done better with the tool than without. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Howard: Thanks man. There&#039;s a great video from 2012 Business of Software you should watch on this subject and I keep forgetting to send your way: &lt;a href=&quot;http://businessofsoftware.org/2013/02/kathy-sierra-building-the-minimum-badass-user-business-of-software-a-masterclass-in-thinking-about-software-product-development/&quot;&gt;Kathy Sierra - Building the Minimum Badass User&lt;/a&gt;
